    <item>
      <title>Policy Compatibility problems with eZ Publish 4.1</title>
      <link>http://projects.ez.no/ezpm/forum/general/policy_compatibility_problems_with_ez_publish_4_1</link>
      <description>Hello,&#13;
&#13;
I'm using eZPrivateMessaging for a little time in eZ Publish 4.1, and I had to face many kernel (1) errors when trying to get the Inbox for a non-admin user.&#13;
&#13;
I tried to set the permissions on "pm" module, but it wasn't in the module list, I had to add in extension "module.ini.append.php" : &lt;code&gt;[ModuleSettings]&#13;
ModuleList[]=pm&lt;/code&gt;&#13;
&#13;
Then I did set the permissions on "pm" module with no restriction, but that didn't remove the error page. I ran into a full-scale debugging, and here's my conclusions :&#13;
&#13;
The extension "module.php" defines a list of functions :&#13;
&lt;code&gt;$FunctionList['create'] = array( );&#13;
$FunctionList['list'] = array( );&#13;
$FunctionList['blacklist'] = array( );&#13;
$FunctionList['contacts'] = array( );&#13;
$FunctionList['send_message'] = array( );&#13;
$FunctionList['add_contact'] = array( );&#13;
$FunctionList['stats'] = array( );&lt;/code&gt;&#13;
But they are never used in the $ViewList items above. So eZ Publish knows that the module requires function-based policies, but the module views actually don't. That's this contradiction that confuse it and prevent it to show the page.&#13;
&#13;
I did comment out the whole $FunctionList definition as they are nowhere to be used, and it finally worked. I could have put a "functions" parameter to each views to make it works too, but it doesn't make sense, you can either have or not the whole access to private messaging.&#13;
&#13;
Hope it helps, great extension otherwise.</description>
      <author>community@ez.no (Hypolite Petovan)</author>
      <guid>http://projects.ez.no/ezpm/forum/general/policy_compatibility_problems_with_ez_publish_4_1</guid>
      <pubDate>Sun, 29 Mar 2009 08:21:04 +0000</pubDate>
    </item>
